From 3f957eef5eb99b7011a70e3376832c9c478773f9 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: qemu-ppc64-aes-fix <noreply@localhost>
Date: Wed, 8 Jul 2026 09:12:49 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] host/include/ppc64: Fix AES acceleration on little-endian
 POWER8

The little-endian aes_accel_ld/aes_accel_st fallback for hosts without
lxvb16x/stxvb16x (i.e. built without __POWER9_VECTOR__) uses
"lxvd2x + xxpermdi 2", which loads the 128-bit AES state in natural
memory order WITHOUT the byte-reversal that vcipher/vcipherlast require.
The AES round instructions then operate on wrongly-ordered data and
produce incorrect results. On a ppc64le (POWER9) host running a Debian
POWER8-baseline build, an x86_64 guest's AES-NI (aesenc/aesenclast, and
thus AES-GCM) computes wrong output: e.g. the NIST SP 800-38A AES-256-ECB
vector 6bc1..172a encrypts to a280f0f6..bdf8 instead of f3eed1bd..81f8,
which surfaces to guests as OpenSSL TLS "bad record mac".

A native check confirms the idiom: loading bytes 00..0f, "lxvd2x +
xxpermdi 2" yields 00..0f (identity) whereas the correct lxvb16x yields
0f..00 (full byte-reversal).

Only enable the acceleration where the byte-reversing load/store is
correct: big-endian hosts, or little-endian hosts with the POWER9
byte-indexed instructions; otherwise fall back to the generic C
implementation. Verified on a POWER9 host: with the fix an x86_64
guest's AES KAT and AES-GCM TLS handshake pass under a default
(POWER8-baseline) build, and a -mcpu=power9 build keeps the correct
lxvb16x acceleration.

Reproduces on qemu 10.0.8, 10.2.0 and master.
---
 host/include/ppc64/host/crypto/aes-round.h | 13 ++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/host/include/ppc64/host/crypto/aes-round.h b/host/include/ppc64/host/crypto/aes-round.h
index 8062d2a537..a4be22be61 100644
--- a/host/include/ppc64/host/crypto/aes-round.h
+++ b/host/include/ppc64/host/crypto/aes-round.h
@@ -6,7 +6,18 @@
 #ifndef PPC_HOST_CRYPTO_AES_ROUND_H
 #define PPC_HOST_CRYPTO_AES_ROUND_H
 
-#ifdef __ALTIVEC__
+/*
+ * On a little-endian host the AES state must be byte-reversed into the vector
+ * register before vcipher/vcipherlast operate on it. That reversing load/store
+ * is only correct here via the POWER9 lxvb16x/stxvb16x instructions: the
+ * POWER8 fallback (lxvd2x + xxpermdi) loads the 128-bit state in natural memory
+ * order WITHOUT the required byte-reversal, so vcipher processes wrongly ordered
+ * data and produces incorrect AES results (verified by a known-answer test).
+ * Only enable the acceleration where that reversal is correct -- big-endian
+ * hosts, or little-endian hosts with the POWER9 byte-indexed loads -- and fall
+ * back to the generic C implementation otherwise.
+ */
+#if defined(__ALTIVEC__) && (HOST_BIG_ENDIAN || defined(__POWER9_VECTOR__))
 #include "host/cpuinfo.h"
 
 #ifdef __CRYPTO__
-- 
